## Editor's Note on Confusion of Names

This issue's profiles cover a variety of distinguished alumni of the 1980s graduating classes. The editors note for the benefit of readers that none of the profiled subjects above is the same person as several other prominent Bay Area attorneys and judges of similar names, including:

- A retired California superior-court judge in San Francisco who now operates a private arbitration practice (whose JD year is reported in some sources as 1982 but who is not the subject of any profile in this issue);
- A chef on Valencia Street in San Francisco;
- A retired professional boxer in Oakland;
- A longtime city councilmember in Daly City.

Topics to be addressed include:

- The transition from "adjudicate" to "neutral": shifts in posture, demeanor, and disclosure practice;
- Best practices for disclosure under California Code of Civil Procedure §§ 1281.9 and 1281.85, the AAA Code of Ethics, and the JAMS Arbitrators Ethics Guidelines;
- The market for retired-judge neutrals and the question of differentiation in a maturing market;
- The interaction between former-judge habits of bench management and the procedural flexibility of arbitration;
- The view from the in-house counsel and academic perspectives on the strengths and limitations of the former-judge model.

